Setup

Before we start exploring and analyzing the data, let’s first load our required packages and data.

Load packages

Load data

With the .RData file in your working directory load the data into your environment.

load("brfss2013.RData")

Part 1: Data

BRFSS Objective

The BRFSS objective is to collect uniform, state-specific data on preventive health practices and risk behaviors that are linked to chronic diseases, injuries, and preventable infectious diseases that affect the adult population.

Data Collection and Sampling

All the information below has been collected from the documentation provided by BRFSS here.The following are the points worth noting regarding the Data Collection and sampling

  • Since 2011, BRFSS conducts both landline-telephone and cellular telephone based surveys. In conducting the BRFSS landline telephone survey, interviewers collect data from a randomly selected adult in a household.
  • To meet the BRFSS standard for the participating states’ sample designs, one must be able to justify sample records as a probability sample of all households with telephones in the state. All participating areas met this criterion in 2013. Fifty-one projects used a disproportionate stratified sample (DSS) design for their landline samples. Guam and Puerto Rico used a simple random-sample design.
  • The basis of the 2013 BRFSS sampling frame is the Telecordia database of telephone exchanges (e.g., 617-492-0000 to 617-492-9999) and 1,000 banks (e.g., 617-492-0000 to 617-492-0999).
  • BRFSS forms an interval, K, by dividing the population count of telephone numbers in the frame, N, by the desired sample size, n. BRFSS divides the frame of telephone numbers into n intervals of size K telephone numbers. From each interval, BRFSS draws one 10-digit telephone number at random.
  • Generalizability: this is an observational study and random sampling methods have been employed in collecting the data, any results arising from the data should be generalizable to the U.S population.
  • Causality: Since this is an observational study and no random assignment has been performed. Causality cannot be inferred.
  • Potential Bias: All the households without a telephone are left out of the sample. Among the users who took the survey through cell phones, only persons residing in a private residence or college housing, who have a working cellular telephone, are aged 18 and older, and received 90 percent or more of their calls on cellular telephones are considered.

    Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

    Research question 1:

    In this question, we want to explore the relationship between income, sleep and life satisfaction. The national sleep foundation recommends the number of hours of sleep according to age as shown in the table below.More info on sleep recommendations here

    Age Group Recommended Appropriate
    65 years+ 7-8 hours 5-6 or 9 hours
    26 - 64 7-9 hours 6 or 10 hours
    18 - 25 7-9 hours 6 or 10-11 hours

    Now let’s create a variable sleep_quality based on _age_g and sleptim1 variables.

    sleptim1 : On average, how many hours of sleep do you get in a 24-hour period?

    Min. 1st Qu. Median Mean 3rd Qu. Max. NA’s
    0 6 7 7.052 8 450 7387

    _age_g : Age category

    Age 18 to 24 Age 25 to 34 Age 35 to 44 Age 45 to 54 Age 55 to 64 Age 65 or older
    27203 50164 60416 83769 109464 160747

    Assuming that the recommended sleep and appropriate sleep ranges as ideal and all others as NR(not recommended). Let’s create the sleep_quality variable accordingly.

    brfss2013 <- brfss2013 %>%
mutate(sleep_quality = 
ifelse(X_age_g == "Age 65 or older" & sleptim1 >= 5 & sleptim1 <= 9, "Ideal",
ifelse(X_age_g == "Age 18 to 24" & sleptim1>=6 & sleptim1<=11, "Ideal",
ifelse(X_age_g != "Age 65 or older" & X_age_g != "Age 18 to 24" & sleptim1>=6 & sleptim1<=10, "Ideal","NR"))))

    Now that we have our sleep_quality variable, let’s see the income2 and lsatisfy variables distributions using frequency tables.

    Let’s create a mosaic plot of the contingenc table above to see if there are any significant patterns.

    mosaicplot(x = table(brfss2013$income2,brfss2013$lsatisfy,brfss2013$sleep_quality),color = 3:2,las = 1,off = 4, main="Relation between household income, sleep quality and life satisfaction",cex.axis = 0.87)

    From the plot above we can clearly infer the following

    Since the proportion of the very satisfied group and the dissatisfied group changes with respect to the household income, we can conclude that they are dependent. In fact as the income rises the satisfaction increases too(the height of bars in each income group repesent the proportion of people belonging to that particular satisfaction group).

    Within each income group, the number of people who have an ideal amount of sleep varies. So we can conclude that they are dependent and by inspection, in general the frequency of ideal sleep decreases with decreasing satisfaction(width of Ideal and NR in each income group represent proportions of sleep quality).

    So clearly the three variables are related. These results can be generalized to persons residing in a private residence or college housing, who have a working cellular telephone, are aged 18 and older, and received 90 percent or more of their calls on cellular telephones.

    Research quesion 2:

    Let’s explore the difference in sleep quality between Smokers and Non-smokers using the variable sleep_quality that we created in the previous research question and _smoker3 variable. The description and frequency tables of these variables are as follows.

    sleep_quality: Whether the person sleeps for a recommended time period according to his age. (NR below means that his sleep timings are not recommended according to his age)

    Ideal NR
    428260 56122

    _smoker3: Four-level smoker status: Everyday smoker, Someday smoker, Former smoker, Non-smoker

    Current smoker - now smokes every day Current smoker - now smokes some days Former smoker Never smoked
    55162 21495 138134 261651

    Since we are interested in noticing the difference between sleep quality of smokers and non-smokers, let’s create a new variable smoker_bool which will group the four categories in _smoker3 varibale into two categories namely smoker and non-smoker.

    brfss2013 <- brfss2013 %>%
mutate(smoker_bool = 
ifelse(X_smoker3 == "Current smoker - now smokes every day" | X_smoker3 == "Current smoker - now smokes some days", "Smokers","Non-Smokers"))

    The frequency table of the smoker_bool variable is as follows

    Non-Smokers Smokers
    399785 76657

    Let’s plot and see if there’s a difference in the sleep quality of smokers and non-smokers.

    plot(table(brfss2013$smoker_bool,brfss2013$sleep_quality),col=3:2,las=1,cex.axis=1.5,main = "Proportions of Smokers and their sleep quality",ylab = "Quality of Sleep")

    We can clearly see that there’s a difference in sleep quality between smokers and non-smokers. But we need to confirm that it did not happen due to random chance. So, let’s design a random experiment to determine if the difference is due to random chance or not.

    Random Experiment

    First let’s check the contingency table of the two variables sleep_quality and smoker_bool and determine the probabilities.

    Ideal NR Total
    Non-Smokers 354871 39361 394232
    Smokers 60477 14939 75416
    Total 415348 54300 469648

    The % of Non-smokers who have an ideal sleep is 354871/394232 = 0.9001578

    The % of Smokers who have an ideal sleep is 60477/75416 = 0.8019121

    The % of people who have an ideal sleep is 415348/469648 = 0.8843815

    The difference in proportions of ideal sleep is 0.9001578-0.8019121 = 0.0982457. So, the null hypothesis and the alternative hypothesis can be described as follows.

    Null Hpothesis(H~0): Smoking and sleep quality are independent. The observed difference is only due to chance.

    Alternative hypothesis(H~A): Smoking and Sleep quality are dependent. Observed difference in proportions is not due to chance.

    Simulation Scheme Now let’s start simulating the experiment. First let’s create a character array which holds the values Ideal and NR representing the ideal and not recommended sleep times respectively. Then create a sample containing a total of 469648 observations which will contain Ideal and NR in the same ratio as of our data. Then we split our sample into smokers and non-smokers such that their proportions also remains intact. Then we take the difference between proportions of ideal sleep among smokers and non-smokers. For this experiment let’s run the simulation 10,000 times.

    names <- c("Ideal","NR")

#create a sample 
sampling <- sample(names, size = 469648, replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.8843815,0.115618))

sampling <- as.data.frame(sampling)

smp_size <- floor(0.1605798 * nrow(sampling))

#Create an array for storing the differences
result <- numeric(10000)

set.seed(68724) #for reproducible results
for(i in 1:10000){
  smoking <- sample(seq_len(469648), size = smp_size)
  Smokers <- sampling[smoking,]
  Non_Smokers <- sampling[-smoking,]
  result[i] <- (table(Smokers)[1]/sum(table(Smokers)))-
                (table(Non_Smokers)[1]/sum(table(Non_Smokers)))
}

    Now that we have our simulated differences let’s plot them

    result <- as.data.frame(result)
gg <- ggplot(result)
gg <- gg + geom_histogram(binwidth=0.0005, colour="black", 
                          aes(x=result,y=..density..*0.0005, fill=..count..))
gg <- gg + scale_fill_gradient("Count", low="#DCDCDC", high="#7C7C7C")

gg <- gg + ylab('') + xlab('') + labs( x = "simulated differences between proportion of ideal sleepers", y = 'proportion of total') + theme(axis.text = element_text(size=18),axis.title = element_text(size=18),legend.text = element_text(size=18))

gg <- gg +  geom_vline(xintercept = 0.0982457)

    We can see from the plot that our observed difference is much greater than the simulated values. So we can conclude that

    We reject the null hypothesis and conclude that smoking affects the sleep of a person.

    Let’s create two datasets from our existing dataframe brfss2013. The exract11 varibale contains the frequency of different types of exercises.

    yoga <- brfss2013 %>%

  filter(exract11 == "Walking")
